5","1500":"1500","Abt 1385":"okolo 1385","1385":"1385","before 1415":"před 1415","Galway, Ireland":"County Galway, Irsko","Clanricarde, Galway, Ireland":"Clanricarde, County Galway, Irsko","Ireland":"Irsko","Clanricarde, galway, Ireland":"Clanricarde, County Galway, Irsko"},"da":{"Abt 1385–1435":"omkring 1385–1435","–Female":"Afdød","1415–1500":"1415–1500","1385–1435":"1385–1435","1415":"1415","1435":"1435","1500":"1500","Abt 1385":"omkring 1385","1385":"1385","before 1415":"før 1415","Galway, Ireland":"County Galway, Irland","Clanricarde, Galway, Ireland":"Clanricarde, County Galway, Irland","Ireland":"Irland","Clanricarde, galway, Ireland":"Clanricarde, County Galway, Irland"},"nl":{"Abt 1385–1435":"circa 1385–1435","–Female":"Overleden","1415–1500":"1415–1500","1385–1435":"1385–1435","1415":"1415","1435":"1435","1500":"1500","Abt 1385":"circa 1385","1385":"1385","before 1415":"vóór 1415","Galway, Ireland":"County Galway, Ierland","Clanricarde, Galway, Ireland":"Clanricarde, County Galway, Ierland","Ireland":"Ierland","Clanricarde, galway, Ireland":"Clanricarde, County Galway, Ierland"},"en":{"Abt 1385–1435":"about 1385–1435","–Female":"Deceased","1415–1500":"1415–1500","1385–1435":"1385–1435","1415":"1415","1435":"1435","1500":"1500","Abt 1385":"about 1385","1385":"1385","before 1415":"before 1415","Galway, Ireland":"County Galway, Ireland","Clanricarde, Galway, Ireland":"Clanricarde, County Galway, Ireland","Ireland":"Ireland","Clanricarde, galway, Ireland":"Clanricarde, County Galway, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Burgh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from one or other of the ten English places named Burgh in northern England and East Anglia, or the six named Brough in Derbyshire, Nottinghamshire, Westmorland, and Yorkshire. All these are from Old English <i>burg</i>, <i>burh</i>, Middle English <i>burgh</i> ‘massive earthwork, fortification; manor, borough’. Compare   Bury  . The placename <i>Burgh</i> is pronounced as <i>borough</i>. The surname   Brough   arose equally from places now called Burgh and Brough, and is the more common form of the surname in modern Britain, where it is pronounced <i>bruff</i> or <i>broof</i> (/brʊf/). The Scottish surname was probably brought in from Yorkshire. For the surname in Ireland see   Burke  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Burke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Kieran, Siobhan, Aileen, Brennan, Brigid, Donovan, Liam, Murphy, Ulick, Aidan, Dermot.","English and Irish (of Anglo-Norman origin): habitational name from Burgh (Castle) in Suffolk, England. <i>Burk</i> represents an Anglo-Norman pronunciation of Old English <i>burg</i>, Middle English <i>burgh</i> ‘fortification’ (see   Burgh  ).","German: variant of   Burk  ."]},{"name":"Bury","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Bury in Lancashire (now part of Greater Manchester), or from some other similarly named place. The placename comes from the dative case, <i>byrig</i>, of Old English <i>burh</i> ‘fortified place’.","Walloon and French: habitational name from any of several places so named, in Wallonia (Belgium) and Oise (France). The placename is from <i>Buriacum</i>, the name of a Gallo-Roman estate, composed of the personal name <i>Burius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>. This surname is also found in the Flemish part of Belgium.","South German: variant of   Buri  ."]},{"name":"Brough","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from any of various English places called Brough or Burgh. See   Burgh  .","Scottish: habitational name from Brough in Harray (Orkney).","Americanized form of German   Brauch   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Burrow","meanings":["English:","topographic name for someone who lived by a castle or manor house, or in a town, especially a chartered town or borough (Middle English <i>burgh</i>, Old English <i>burg</i> ‘fortified place, borough, manor’), or a habitational name for someone who came from a place so named because it was a fortified town or near an ancient fort, such as Burrow (Leicestershire, Lancashire), Burrough Green (Cambridgeshire), Brough (numerous counties), and Peterborough (Northamptonshire); see also   Burgh  .","topographic name for someone who lived on a hill or near a mound (Middle English <i>bergh</i>, Old English <i>beorg</i>), or a habitational name for someone who came from a place so named, such as Burrow (Devon, Somerset). Middle English <i>bergh</i> became throughly confused with <i>burgh</i> in 1 above. Compare   Burrough  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]},{"name":"Macwilliam","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scottish Iain, Morag.","Scottish and Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Uilleim</b>, a patronymic from a Gaelicized form of   William  , also Anglicized as   Williamson   in Scotland. The name is thought to be mainly Scottish in Ulster, though there has been some confusion with   McQuillan   in County Down. In Connacht, McWilliam was a branch of   Burke  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Quilliam","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> ."]},{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Walter Macwilliam Burgh was born about 1385, in Clanricarde, County Galway, Ireland. He married Mrs Walter MacWilliam Burgh before 1415, in Ireland. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1435, in County Galway, Ireland, at the age of 51."},"et":{"Abt 1385–1435":"umbes 1385–1435","–Female":"Surnud","1415–1500":"1415–1500","1385–1435":"1385–1435","1415":"1415","1435":"1435","1500":"1500","Abt 1385":"umbes 1385","1385":"1385","before 1415":"enne 1415","Galway, Ireland":"County Galway, Iirimaa","Clanricarde, Galway, Ireland":"Clanricarde, County Galway, Iirimaa","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Clanricarde, galway, Ireland":"Clanricarde, County Galway, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1385–1435":"noin 1385–1435","–Female":"Kuollut","1415–1500":"1415–1500","1385–1435":"1385–1435","1415":"1415","1435":"1435","1500":"1500","Abt 1385":"noin 1385","1385":"1385","before 1415":"ennen vuotta 1415","Galway, Ireland":"County Galway, Irlanti","Clanricarde, Galway, Ireland":"Clanricarde, County Galway, Irlanti","Ireland":"Irlanti","Clanricarde, galway, Ireland":"Clanricarde, County Galway, Irlanti"},"fr":{"Abt 1385–1435":"environ 1385–1435","–Female":"Décédée","1415–1500":"1415–1500","1385–1435":"1385–1435","1415":"1415","1435":"1435","1500":"1500","Abt 1385":"environ 1385","1385":"1385","before 1415":"avant 1415","Galway, Ireland":"County Galway, Irlande","Clanricarde, Galway, Irelan